transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Hi. Thank you so much for calling Viagra. My name is Jessie. Can I get your first and last name?

Speaker 2: Yes. Eric Kelly.

Speaker 1: Eric Kelly?

Speaker 2: Yes, ma'am.

Speaker 1: All right. Super. Mr. Kelly, what can I help you with?

Speaker 2: I just placed an order online, and when I put my e-mail address in, it actually put my – I guess it auto-filled my old e-mail address.

Speaker 1: So I'm getting the text messages, but when I try to log in, it won't let me log in because of it.

Speaker 2: Oh. Oh, gotcha. Okay. Let me go ahead and change your e-mail.

Speaker 1: And also, just so you know, you can always log in with your phone number.

Speaker 2: So the option log in with phone, it sends you a code, and you use the code to log in.

Speaker 1: But I will change your e-mail if you'd like. If you don't mind, Mr. Kelly, can I get your zip code?

Speaker 2: Yes, 32904.

Speaker 1: Perfect. Are you at 577 Edward Road in Melbourne, Florida?

Speaker 2: Yes.

Speaker 1: All right. What's the correct e-mail?

Speaker 2: The correct e-mail is – instead of 73, it should be 25.

Speaker 1: Oh, gotcha. So it's like Cousin Rick, that's C-U-Z-N-R-I-C, at 25 at your e-mail?

Speaker 2: Yes, ma'am.

Speaker 1: Okay. Let me update that.

Speaker 2: Oh, it looks like you might have – okay. Let me just fix this here.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: Okay, one moment.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: All right. I've sent this over to our admin team, and they will update your e-mail address.

Speaker 1: In the meantime, like I said, you can always use log in with phone.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: Honestly, I tell people to use it all the time because you don't have to remember a username and password anymore.

Speaker 2: You'll always have your phone with you.

Speaker 1: Right, right, right.

Speaker 2: Is there anything else I can help you with?

Speaker 1: No, ma'am. That'll be it. Thank you so much.

Speaker 2: No problem. Thank you. Have a good day. Bye-bye.

Speaker 1: Bye-bye.
